+// pipe.c's own comment for why). A regular file's read() returns 0 the
+// instant the read offset reaches the current end of content, regardless of
+// whether a writer might still append more later — unlike a real pipe, which
+// blocks until either more data arrives or every write end is closed. That
+// distinction stopped being free once every fork (Phase 4) — including the
+// implicit ones dash creates for each pipeline stage — went through the
+// scheduler instead of running to completion before returning: nothing
+// guarantees the writer stage runs (or finishes) before the reader stage
+// gets its first turn now, so the reader can see "0 bytes so far" and wrongly
+// conclude real EOF. This refcount is the fix: track how many write-end Fds
+// (across every independent fork-child fd table a dup can land in) are still
+// open for a given pipe, so the read side can tell "genuinely done" from
+// "nothing written yet, try again" (see SysRead) — the same distinction a
+// real kernel pipe makes internally.
+struct MvlPipeRef {
+  int refcount;  // live write-end Fd references; 0 = true EOF for the reader
+};
